<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by P Goddard</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">AFS17</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by P Goddard</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Re: Education Select Committee Inquiry into Academies &amp; Free Schools</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">I am writing this submission as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">a parent of school aged children and a member of a group of like-minded people. Parents are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">becomi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">ng increasingly concerned over </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">lack of engagement with, and representation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> parents in their children’s educa</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">tion, particularly relating</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> to the academy and free school</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> programme.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">It is too early to say whether the academy programme </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">will result in long-term rises in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">educational standards.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The consultation process is deeply flawed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Parents, pupils and local stakeholders have fewer opportunities to hold decision makers to account, including headteachers, academy trustees, governors and sponsors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">There is too little oversight and too little accoun</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">tability of academies and free schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">There is a lack of evidence to show whether </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the academy programme is really bene</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">fitting disadvantaged children</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">There has been a great deal of debate lately over the electorate’s lack of engagement in politics and democracy in this country and this is a typical example of why people feel disenfranchised. As parents, wishing to help our children in their education, we are effectively sidelined for all the significant decisions involved in whether</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> or how</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> a school becomes an academy and on having any real influence over the governance and ethos of these establishments.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">1.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">academisation</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.1.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The current academies programme has only been operating for a little over three years now and I believe that it is too early to draw any concrete conclusions over the effectiveness of this policy when it comes to the quality of education for our </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">children and young people, including those considered disadvantaged.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">We are told that it is too soon</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> for the academy programme to have had an</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> effect on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the 2012 PISA tests, the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">results</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> and rankings of which have recently been released. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Yet, we are also told that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the academy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">programme is having an immediate transformative effect o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">n education, resulting in apparently</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> overnight boosts to examination results in those new academies. Clearly, there is a discrepancy here and test and exam</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ination</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> results are only part of the picture in any case. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Where is the evidence of real, substantive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> improveme</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">nt in the quality of our children’s education in academies? Or are the improvements on paper only, e.g. better exam results due to successful academy headteachers being more “clued up” on the easier exam syllabi, how to teach to test, how to target “failing” pupils for intervention work shortly before exams (after years of poor progress) or how to exclude “difficult” students? How often are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">apparent improvement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">s due </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to other variables, such as manipulating the intake</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> through changing admission arrangements? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Since “outstanding” schools that convert to academy status are not subject to Ofsted inspections, it is nigh on impossible for them to lose their “outstanding” ratings. But, of course, standards can fall as well as rise. So, data that shows increasing numbers of “outstanding” and “good” academies, does not take into effect the fact that falling standards might not be routinely picked up. Only if test or exam passes dramatically fall or a whistleblower alerts the authorities to problems, would Ofsted step in.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">How does</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> hiring non-qualified teachers raise standards?</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> The most successful education systems in the world value their teaching professionals, hold them in high regard and, insisting on high qualifications.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.6 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">How can it be deemed important for maintained schools to follow the National Curriculum, yet not for academies and free schools, where controversial curricula, can be taught?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.7</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Academies are allowed to give priority in their admission arrangements to children eligible for Free School Meals. How many actually do this? Surely, if all schools, including successful maintained schools and faith schools were </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">compelled to give priority to FSM children, we would see a marked improveme</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">nt in outcomes for these groups as they would have better access to good schools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.8 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Some sponsored academies that change their admission arrangements, actually reduce the numbers of Free School Meal and Special Education Needs pupils, e.g. by bringing in “Fair Banding” whereby children with higher academic achievements from further afield can displace local disadvantaged children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">1.9</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">It is an accepted view in most circles that children’s educational outcomes are affected by the levels of parental involvement and support and that the best schools work in collaboration with parents to help their pupils reach their potential. Unfortunately, converting a school to an academy does nothing to address this issue. In fact, my own experienc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">e with one academy is that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the level of communication with parents went rapidly downhill within months of its conversion. Gone were the regular newsletters, parent post and the yearly traditional written parent reports. A more expensive uniform was introduced for the academy’s sixth form, without consultation with parents, which is clearly not in the best interests of poorer, disadvantaged families.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/lisa.d.lanchester"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/lisa.d.lanchester"></a><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">2.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Parents are sidelined from all the important decisions, both over whether schools convert in the first place, and over how they are run once they become academies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">2.2 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Academies Act 2010 states “Consultation on conversion</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Before a maintained school in England is converted into an Academy, the school’s governing body must consult such persons as they think appropriate. The consultation must be on the question of whether the school should be converted into an Academy. The consultation may take place before or after an Academy order, or an application for an Academy order, has been made in respect of the school.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">There are cases where parents have not been consulted until after the Secretary of State has signed the academy order and chosen the sponsor, e.g</span><span style="color:#800000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Roke Primary School</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, Croydon.</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> How can such a consultation be meaningful?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Parents have little or no say over the trustees or the sponsor, which can have a huge effect on a school, with many ramifications. The ethos of a school can be significantly altered on becoming an academy, depending on the trustees and governors. It is even possible for academies to introduce a faith ethos into a formerly non-faith designated school, without consulting parents.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Parents generally do not have a free choice over which school or academy their children attend in the first place, but when the governance and ethos of a school dramatically changes part way through a child’s time at that school, as is possible on academisation, it is not easy and certainly not ideal for the parents to have to look for alternative educational provision.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">2.6 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">There have been many cases in the news lately where previously good schools have received “requires improvement” or “inadequate” Ofsted judgments and these have often led to “compelled” </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">or “forced” </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">academisat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ion, despite overwhelming </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">opposition from the schools, parents and other local people. Whereas, clearly, poor standards cannot be allowed to go unchallenged, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">some of these cases, e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Bournville School and Sixth Form in Birmingham</span><span style="color:#800000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">a good school which has</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> decided not to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">convert to academy status, has been subjected to an Ofsted inspection shortly thereafter, subsequently downgraded and forced into becoming a sponsored academy. It makes many local people</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> question the role of Ofsted in the academy programme and whether it is an impartial body.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">3.0 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">he role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">3.1 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Since this inquiry was announced, </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the Secretary of State has announced </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Regional School Commissioners and panels of head</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">teachers to oversee academies and free schools in the future. Will this new arrangement lead to conflicts of interest? Will heads on the regional boards press for "</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">failing" academies </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to join their own academy chains?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/rich.morgan.3958"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/rich.morgan.3958"></a><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">4.0 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">he functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of loc</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">al authorities and other organis</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">ations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">There should be a local level of oversight and accountability. I do not thin</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">k the newly announced Regional School Commissioners and </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">panels of head</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">teacher</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">s will be sufficient.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Local Authority or another loca</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">body </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">elected by and accountable to </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the p</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ublic),</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> should be responsible for coordinating important fun</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ctions, e.g. school admission arrangements; school places;</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> coordinating partnerships betwee</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">n schools to narrow the gap, raise standards and share best practices; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">helping parents and families where</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> they have issues with schools and a</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">cademies</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, e.g. expensive school</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> uniforms or poor communication; and </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">providing advice and guidance to h</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">eads and governors at all schools and academies, when needed. Not all academy heads and governors have the expertise they need, e.g. over legal duties, whereas Local Authorities have decades of experience in such areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Obviously, parents can</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> take</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> up issues over policies and practices directly with academies, through the academies’ own complaints procedures.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> But these can take months to reach conclusion an</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">d there is no recourse</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">if the parents ar</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">e dissatisfied with the outcome</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, other than raising the issue wi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">th the Department for Education.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> In any case, I expect the DfE will only be interested in significant issues such as financial mismanagement or serious failings i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">n key measures. M</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ny parents may be wary of making</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> official complaint</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">in the first place, fearing negative ramifications for their children. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">4.4 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Academies have to include parent governors on their boards, but it can be as few a two parent governors for academies over 1200+ pupils and often their existence is not promoted and parents not encouraged to contact these people who are supposed to be a voice for all parents within an academy or school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">4.5  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Therefore,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> it is imperative that parents have a local, accessible</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> service for raising issues over the running of all schools, including academies and free schools</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">To give one example of where I believe local coordination is vital within the education system: L</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ocal police have recently informed schools </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">in my area </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">potentially serious incidents </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">involving one or more adults targeting young girls. The police</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> asked the schools </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">and academies </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to relay the inform</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ation to students and parents. It seems not all academies have done so. The Local A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">uthori</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ty should be able to compel all </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">schools to do this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">5.0 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">hat role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">5.1 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">I am not clear how academy chains are accountable to anyone other than shareholders, if linked to businesses or private sponsors. They are not subject to Ofsted inspections.</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">5.2 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">How much oversight and accountability is there in the system? How do we know that contracts for services for academies in a chain are put out to competitive tender? Or are companies owned by or run by friends, family and associates of the directors given favourable treatment</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> in the </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">handing out se</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">rvice contracts, as alleged at the Kings Science Academy. Individuals and c</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ompanies providing servi</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ces to academies can do so for profits. But, t</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">here seem to be many cases where the academy sponsors and chains a</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">re directly linked to businesses that are run for profit, or the lines are blurred.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">5.3</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Amongst my other concerns is that one academy chain can have a near monopoly over schools in a particular loc</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ation. For instance, I understand that </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">in Pimlico, London, 3 out of 4 primaries are part of the same academy chain (Lord Nash's Future Academies Chain). This cannot be good for parental choice or healthy competition.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">5.4 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Once a school joins an academy chain, the governing body for the chain can apparently reorganize classes, merging schools or moving classes or year groups between different academies in the chain, without any requirement to hold a consultation with parents, e.g. Chumleigh Academy Trust, Devon.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">5.5</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">As academy chains grow and reap the cost benefits of the economy of scale, the reverse may occur within Local Authorities, to the point where maintained primary schools may be effectively forced to join academy cha</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ins as services provided by the LA become too expensive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">5.6</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Can academ</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">y chains become too big to fail, e.g. E-Act?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">6.0 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">6.1 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Is it really in the best interest of a primary school to be part of an academy chain led by a secondary academy? Will the leadership at the secondary be best placed to advise on primary matters? Will there be conflicts of interest when league tables start giving more weight to progress measu</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">res rather than just raw test or </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">exam results, e.g. could a lead secondary academy be tempted to suppress high achievements in primary academies in its chain</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to take the credit itself by </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">showing apparently impressive progress with its own intake? Is the power skewed in academy chai</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ns towards the secondary academy(i</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> in the chain?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a href="https://www.facebook.com/penny.busby.52"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/penny.busby.52"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">6.2</span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#2d4486; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">However, a single primary school may be too small to go</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> it alone as a converter academy, </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">with al</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">l the demands of autonomy, but </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">without the </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">benefits of Local Authority</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">support. </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">It </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">would have little</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> "buyi</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ng power" for services and would not be able to</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> do </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">all the functions</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> itself. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">7.0 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">hat alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">7.1</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">Partnerships, federations or better support from the local authority are measures that have worked in the past. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">7.2 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">              </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">There was much talk of successful academies sponsoring failing schools, but so many of these academies do not seem interested in helping other schools with large numbers of pupils</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt"> eligible for Free School Meals or with Special Educational Needs </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">or </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">schools </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">located in poorer areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">7.3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">One </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">local secondary academy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">trust </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">has recently taken over a “failing” primary school. It has turned it around from an undersubscribed junior school, with nearly one third of its students qualifying for Free School Meals, into an oversubscribed primary academy with its latest intake of 30 pupils including just ONE pupil eligible for FSM.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The academy trust </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">could have given prefer</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ence to FSM children in its local secondary academy’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">and its sponsored primary academy’s admission arrangements. It did not. Instead it chose to give feeder status </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">for admissions to the “outstanding” secondary academy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to that primary academy. Almost overnight the sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">primary </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">academy “improved” by becoming oversubscribed in its admissions. Pupils there are now guaranteed a place at the successful secondary academy.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> Has there been </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">an improvement in teaching or educational outcomes at</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the primary academy? It is too early to know.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> But certainly, it does not appear that many FSM children will benefit if there has been.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>